 succeeded in 1016ms:
Analysis summary for ds001_aml

The cohort contains 50000 AML patient records with no missing values in the analyzed columns. The overall objective_response rate was 18.8%.

Across 25 propose-test-update iterations, the strongest supported patterns were treatment-biomarker specificity and adverse-risk biology. Venetoclax/azacitidine, 7+3, and the targeted FLT3/IDH agents all showed positive unadjusted associations with objective_response. The largest and most specific response gains appeared when targeted therapies matched their biomarkers: midostaurin in flt3_itd disease, gilteritinib in FLT3-altered disease, ivosidenib in idh1_mutation disease, and enasidenib in idh2_mutation disease. Interaction tests generally supported this specificity, including adjusted linear-probability interaction models for midostaurin by flt3_itd, ivosidenib by idh1_mutation, enasidenib by idh2_mutation, and gilteritinib by flt3_any.

Adverse disease biology was consistently associated with lower response. tp53_mutation had an unadjusted risk difference of -2.4% and remained negative after adjustment (-2.5%). complex_karyotype had an unadjusted risk difference of -2.3% and remained negative after adjustment (-2.4%). secondary_aml, unfit_for_intensive, older age, worse ECOG performance status, higher inflammatory markers, higher WBC/blast burden, and higher LDH were also associated with lower response probability in the expected direction.

Favorable-risk biology was also visible. npm1_mutation was associated with higher response unadjusted (6.7%) and after adjustment (6.8%). IDH-mutated disease showed a positive main-effect association, and IDH-mutated patients treated with venetoclax/azacitidine had higher response than IDH-mutated patients not treated with that regimen.

Fitness-stratified treatment patterns were clinically coherent. Venetoclax/azacitidine showed a strong positive association among unfit_for_intensive patients and also among secondary_aml patients. 7+3 showed a strong positive association among fit patients, while the 7+3 by unfit_for_intensive interaction was negative, indicating weaker benefit in the unfit subgroup.

Several non-AML or likely decoy variables were probed. Solid-tumor alteration fields such as her2_amplification, met_exon14_skipping, and ros1_fusion had small or inconsistent associations compared with canonical AML biomarkers. Effusion/metastasis-like fields and broad comorbidity markers generally had weaker effects than molecular risk, treatment, fitness, and inflammatory disease-burden variables.

Overall conclusion: objective_response in this cohort is shaped by matched therapy-biomarker relationships, with strong positive interactions for FLT3- and IDH-directed therapies, and by baseline AML risk/fitness factors. TP53 mutation, complex karyotype, secondary AML, unfitness, older age, worse ECOG, inflammatory state, and higher disease burden mark lower response, while NPM1 mutation and biomarker-matched targeted therapy mark higher response.

