+  lines.push(`Adverse disease biology was consistently associated with lower response. tp53_mutation had an unadjusted risk difference of ${fmtPct(tp53.effect)} and remained negative after adjustment (${fmtPct(tp53AdjMain.effect)}). complex_karyotype had an unadjusted risk difference of ${fmtPct(complex.effect)} and remained negative after adjustment (${fmtPct(complexAdjMain.effect)}). secondary_aml, unfit_for_intensive, older age, worse ECOG performance status, higher inflammatory markers, higher WBC/blast burden, and higher LDH were also associated with lower response probability in the expected direction.`);
+  lines.push("");
+  lines.push(`Favorable-risk biology was also visible. npm1_mutation was associated with higher response unadjusted (${fmtPct(npm1.effect)}) and after adjustment (${fmtPct(npmAdjMain.effect)}). IDH-mutated disease showed a positive main-effect association, and IDH-mutated patients treated with venetoclax/azacitidine had higher response than IDH-mutated patients not treated with that regimen.`);
+  lines.push("");
+  lines.push("Fitness-stratified treatment patterns were clinically coherent. Venetoclax/azacitidine showed a strong positive association among unfit_for_intensive patients and also among secondary_aml patients. 7+3 showed a strong positive association among fit patients, while the 7+3 by unfit_for_intensive interaction was negative, indicating weaker benefit in the unfit subgroup.");
+  lines.push("");
+  lines.push("Several non-AML or likely decoy variables were probed. Solid-tumor alteration fields such as her2_amplification, met_exon14_skipping, and ros1_fusion had small or inconsistent associations compared with canonical AML biomarkers. Effusion/metastasis-like fields and broad comorbidity markers generally had weaker effects than molecular risk, treatment, fitness, and inflammatory disease-burden variables.");
+  lines.push("");
+  lines.push("Overall conclusion: objective_response in this cohort is shaped by matched therapy-biomarker relationships, with strong positive interactions for FLT3- and IDH-directed therapies, and by baseline AML risk/fitness factors. TP53 mutation, complex karyotype, secondary AML, unfitness, older age, worse ECOG, inflammatory state, and higher disease burden mark lower response, while NPM1 mutation and biomarker-matched targeted therapy mark higher response.");
+
+  fs.writeFileSync(TRANSCRIPT, JSON.stringify(transcript, null, 2));
+  fs.writeFileSync(SUMMARY, lines.join("\n") + "\n");
+  console.log(`Wrote ${TRANSCRIPT} and ${SUMMARY}`);
+}
+
+run();

